# 1. Docker Image Layers

## What are Docker Layers?

A Docker image is **not a single file**.

It is made up of multiple **read-only layers**.

Each instruction in a Dockerfile creates a new layer.

Example:

```dockerfile
FROM ubuntu

RUN apt update

RUN apt install -y git

COPY notes.txt .

CMD ["bash"]
```

Layers created:

```text
Layer 5 → CMD ["bash"]

Layer 4 → COPY notes.txt .

Layer 3 → RUN apt install -y git

Layer 2 → RUN apt update

Layer 1 → FROM ubuntu
```

Every instruction creates a separate layer.

---

# 2. Why does Docker create layers?

Docker creates layers mainly because of **Layer Caching**.

Instead of rebuilding the complete image every time, Docker reuses the layers that have not changed.

This makes image building:

* Faster
* More storage efficient
* Reusable

---

# Example

Dockerfile:

```dockerfile
FROM ubuntu

RUN apt update

RUN apt install -y git

COPY notes.txt .

CMD ["bash"]
```

Suppose only **notes.txt** changes.

Docker will reuse:

```text
FROM ubuntu

RUN apt update

RUN apt install -y git
```

Docker will rebuild:

```text
COPY notes.txt .

CMD ["bash"]
```

Docker starts rebuilding from the **first changed layer onward**.

---

# Docker Layer Cache

Think of building a house.

House:

```text
Foundation

Walls

Roof

Paint
```

Tomorrow only paint changes.

Do we rebuild the entire house?

No.

Only paint changes.

Docker works in exactly the same way.

---

# Best Practice

Expensive operations should be placed before frequently changing files.

Good Dockerfile:

```dockerfile
FROM ubuntu

RUN apt update

RUN apt install -y python3

RUN apt install -y git

COPY app.py .

CMD ["python3","app.py"]
```

Reason:

Developers change app.py frequently.

Docker can reuse the installation layers.

