# Interview Questions

## What are Docker Layers?

Docker layers are read-only layers created by each instruction in a Dockerfile. Together they form a Docker image.

---

## Why are Docker Layers important?

Docker layers allow layer caching, making image builds faster and reducing storage usage.

---

## What is Layer Cache?

Docker reuses unchanged layers during image build and rebuilds only from the first modified layer onwards.

---

## What does docker history do?

It displays all layers used to build an image along with their creation commands, size and timestamps.

---

## What does docker images do?

Lists all Docker images available on the local system.

---

## What does docker rmi do?

Deletes a Docker image from the local system.

---

## What does docker tag do?

Creates another name or version tag for an existing image without creating a duplicate image.

---

# Key Takeaways

✔ A Docker image is made up of multiple layers.

✔ Each Dockerfile instruction creates a new layer.

✔ Docker uses layer caching to avoid rebuilding unchanged layers.

✔ docker history helps us understand image layers.

✔ docker images lists local images.

✔ docker rmi removes images.

✔ docker tag creates another reference (tag) to the same image.

✔ Changing a Dockerfile does NOT modify an existing image. A new image must be built using docker build.

